lved 4 stages: %0a%3c Stage 1 = deletion of clicks in words %0a%3c Stage 2 = simplification process (c>tand q>tandx>t/k) %0a%3c Stage 3 = click substitution (c>qandx>c/qandq>c/x) %0a%3c Stage 4 = click accompaniments materialise (ch>ncandgc>c)%0a%3c Stage 5 = acquisition of clicks %0a%3c For the native speaking babies, the “appearance of all basic clicks is between 1 and 1:6 years”. They also found that the babies acquired voiceless clicks first, followed by voiced and nasal clicks.%0a%3c  %0a%3c Another interesting thing I learned was that the clicking languages are extremely old. According to the article, clicks “seem to have been part of the first fully articulate human language that appeared among some group of early human language that appeared among some group of early humans 50,000 years ago.”%0a%3c  %0a%3c In another article I found, “Left-Hemisphere Advantage for Click Consonants Is Determined by Linguistic Significance and Experience” by Catherine T. Best and Robert A. Avery, the authors specifically focused on speech recognition and how left-hemisphere populations have a much higher aptitude for recognizing consonants. The theory discussed is called the LH (left-Hemisphere) advantage, and employed a study which assessed Zulu vs. English speakers’ click recognition. The English speakers auditorily recognized the clicks as non-speech sounds, but only the Zulu speakers were able to retain the sounds with linguistic significance, (for instance, having the ability to distinguish [ǂ] from [ǁ]) because their language uses clicks as consonants. In this way, the Zulus showed an LH advantage.%0a%3c  %0a%3c Articles: %0a%3c Acquisition of clicks study: https://perlinguam.journals.ac.za/pub/article/viewFile/81/165%0a%3c %0a%3c Left-Hemisphere Advantage for Click Consonants: https://www-jstor-org.cmu.idm.oclc.org/stable/40063379?seq=1#metadata_info_tab_contents%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c (:Category:)%0a\ No newline at end of 